\chapter{Creole and Cajun Network Structures}
  \label{chap:networks}
  Having established that subject pronoun realizations can mark speakers as Creole or Cajun (or Black or White), a natural next step is examining the social context of which this language variation is indicative.
  When dealing with ethnic and racial language variation, there is evidence that linguistic behavior is related to social segregation between the groups involved \parencite{duncan_residential_2018, kohn_segregation_2018}.
  Intuitively, this makes sense: if two groups of people have little contact with each other, they will not expose each other to their linguistic behaviors, and thus their speech patterns will not converge.
  Segregation on some level is perhaps also an inherent aspect of racialization \parencite{andersson_racialization_2003, smith_residential_1993}.
  In essence, if Creoles and Cajuns are racialized groups, then one should expect to see segregation, and that segregation would go hand in hand with distinct linguistic patterns for the two groups.
  The objective of this chapter is therefore to determine whether the data gathered shows evidence of segregation.

  Besides \foreign{de jure} segregation that is often laid out explicitly and relatively plainly in legislation, there are many quantitative means of establishing the existence of segregation between two groups \parencite{fossett_new_2017}.
  For the sort of general racial or ethnic segregation of interest in the present study, social network analysis was employed.
  Primarily, ethnic homophily of the personal social networks, meaning the extent to which participants' social contacts are ethnically identical to themselves, was analyzed as a proxy for whether or not Creole and Cajun speakers of F\&C are segregated in Lafayette and the surrounding communities.

