  \section{Social network analysis}
    Social network analysis has a long history in sociolinguistic research starting primarily with \citeauthor{milroy_language_1987}'s (\citeyear{milroy_language_1987}) application to the communities she studied in Belfast, Ireland.
    While this approach has found notable uses in the field since then \parencite[\foreign{e.g.}][]{dodsworth_social_2017, li_two-step_2000, paolillo_virtual_1999, sharma_scalar_2017}, the vast majority of methodological developments have occurred in other fields, notably sociology, mathematics, and computer science, a very brief overview of which will be relevant to will be covered here.

    A network was originally defined as a social field of a given individual made up of their friends and kin where links to the individual represented interaction of some sort \parencite[p.~43]{barnes_class_1954}.
    Visually, this can be represented as points (\foreign{e.g.}, friends and kin) and lines (\foreign{e.g.}, interactions).
    These points are typically referred to as nodes or vertices and these lines as ties or edges.
    Nodes often often represent individuals, as they do in the present study, but can also represent organizations or other social entities, and in the broader field of network theory, they can be almost anything, from web pages to terminals in an electrical circuit.
    % A liaison person is a point in a network which links two network sectors and whose ties to one or both of those sectors are all weak, often being a point at one end of a bridge (Granovetter 1973:1367-1368)

    Ties are perhaps more complex in what they may represent as they are generally more abstract.
    While originally conceptualized as representing interactions, which is still inherently an aspect of ties, there are various types of interactions -- those one has with close friends or with a bank teller or with a boss -- which can be further specified by measuring the frequency of those interactions, placing a value on each type of interaction, and identifying whether interactions are one direction or bi-directional.
    In essence, one is measuring not only interactions but also the strength of those interactions or in other words the strength of ties \parencite{granovetter_strength_1973}.
    In practice, much of this is difficult to measure, so often proxies are used to quantify the strength of a tie.
    For instance, in \citeauthor{milroy_language_1987}'s (\citeyear{milroy_language_1987}) case, she simply identified the relationship between the two nodes as being between kin, neighbors, coworkers, or friends (p.~52), each of which made up an attributes of ties but were equally weighted between each other.
