    Measuring the strength of ties is just one of the many ways in which networks can be quantified, that quantification being the primary advantage of this approach.
    Another example would be quantifying social distance as the shortest path between two nodes \parencite[p.~1366]{granovetter_strength_1973}.
    In sociolinguistics, the quantificational nature of social network analysis has been noted as lending itself well to analyzing interaction patterns and the spread of linguistic change \parencite[pp.~262-263]{dodsworth_speech_2014}.
    Importantly, measures can be taken that apply to personal (or egocentric) networks or total networks \parencite[p.~250]{bott_family_1971}.
    While the analyses carried out here are primarily carried out on personal networks, there are some analyses of the total network, as well.
    It is thus important to have a general understanding of each type of analysis.
    % social network analysis has been noted for being particularly useful for analyzing communities where macro-social variables such as social class are not relevant \parencite[pp.~172-173]{milroy_language_1987}
    % Social networks have two types of information: structural (simply the geometry of who is connected to who) and 2) content/quality (the strength of ties, direction, attributes of individuals, etc.) (Sharma 2017:395)
      % Sharma (2017) concluded that network qualities are more culturally and historically contingent and so may not generalize across space and time (in her case, the Asianness or Indianness of one's network only mattered for some demographics), but network structures are general and not bounded in this way (in her case, the diversity index of network clusters in one's network was significant for all demographics) (414-415)

    Total or whole network analysis is what it sounds like, and possibly what most people think of when first learning about social network analysis, and that is the analysis of an entire community or set of communities using a network approach.
    It is essentially the macro-social level of social network analysis.
    This is also what makes this sort of analysis, when applied to social networks, much rarer than personal network analysis in that it is contingent on elaborating all network nodes and ties.
    A truly valid total network analysis must not leave any part of the network unaccounted for as all nodes and ties will impact the statistics that are then generated.
    Total network analysis is therefore usually conducted for very small, discrete, well-defined communities such as the classic study of a karate club \parencite{zachary_information_1977}, or it is conducted for communities where only very specific, easily documented types of ties are used for a strictly delineated area, such as actors appearing in feature films listed on the website IMDb where ties are simply those with whom they have co-starred in these films \parencite{watts_networks_1999}.

    This type of analysis can highlight useful information, however.
    Some classic examples include calculating the density of a network, meaning the ratio of actual ties to possible ties that represents whether a network is close-knit or loose-knit (\citeauthor{barnes_networks_1968}, \citeyear[p.~118]{barnes_networks_1968}; \citeauthor{bott_family_1971}, \citeyear[p.~59]{bott_family_1971}), or calculating the dispersion of the network as the sum of all of its internal distances \parencite[p.~727]{bavelas_communication_1950}.
    There are always various community detection algorithms that act on the structural properties of the network \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][]{aslak_constrained_2017, newman_finding_2004, waltman_smart_2013}.
    Communities in this case, then, are defined as dense clusters within a network that highlight heavy interaction.
    Relatedly, the centrality of different components of the total network or within detected communities can be quantified in numerous ways.
    Some of these identify important ties in the network \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][]{freeman_set_1977}, while most identify important nodes \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][]{brin_anatomy_1998, katz_new_1953, kleinberg_hubs_1999, kleinberg_authoritative_1999, rochat_closeness_2009}.
    In sociolinguistics, this last class of analyses have been the main form carried out, often somewhat crudely, for purposes such as establishing individuals who are sociolinguistic ``stars'' or ``icons'' (\citeauthor{eckert_linguistic_2000}, \citeyear[pp.~216-219]{eckert_linguistic_2000}; \citeauthor{labov_principles_2001}, \citeyear[p.~350]{labov_principles_2001}).
