    The other approach to social network analysis, that of personal (or egocentric) network analysis, is far less demanding of resources to carry out than total network analysis, which likely explains why it is these analyses that have been carried out in more traditional-looking variationist sociolinguistics studies \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][]{sharma_style_2011, sharma_scalar_2017}.
    Ego, in this case, refers to the node whose perspective is taken in the analysis, leaving all other nodes connected to ego either directly or indirectly to be referred to as alters \parencite[p.~6]{perry_egocentric_2018}.
    In practice, the alters who are collected for ego in such analyses are only those who are directly connected, making up what is called a primary or first-order star network, named as such because a resulting graph of the network would form a star with ego at the center.
    Alternatively, one may include the whole primary or first-order zone, which would add any existing ties between ego's direct alters, or even second-order or $n$th-order zones, which bring these analyses to a point of looking more like total network analyses \parencite[pp.~113-114]{barnes_networks_1968}.
    Calculating statistics for personal networks is essentially about quantifying aspects of an individuals social world.
    Data collected might include the mix of ethnicities, nationalities, or genders of ego's network \parencite{botha_social_2018, li_two-step_2000, sharma_scalar_2017}, as just a few examples.
    Likewise, the primary data collected for personal networks in the present study was their ethnic make-ups, specifically to the ends of determining if there is evidence of segregation between Creoles and Cajuns.

