  \section{Methods}
    \label{sec:network_methods}
    The question of whether there is segregation between Creoles and Cajuns was examined here by analyzing ethnic homophily in the social networks of participants.
    To do this, network data was collected for each participant.
    This raised a few challenges related to how to ask for alters and how to gather information on those alters, all of which will be discussed in section \ref{sec:network_collection}.
    The quantitative analyses carried out consisted of relatively straightforward descriptive statistics, but there were important decisions made about how to prepare the data for calculating those statistics which will be discussed in section \ref{sec:network_analyses}.

    \subsection{Data collection}
      \label{sec:network_collection}
      The data used for the analysis of personal networks came from the same participants as the analysis of subject pronoun variation.
      Network questioned were asked during the same interviews, and almost all participants responded to these questions.
      The two exceptions were Rachel Chenevert, a Creole, and Errol Stoufle, a Cajun.
      The target for interview lengths was an hour with network questions coming last in most cases.\footnote{
        Technically, the transcription task was left for last but was skipped for most participants.
      } This duration has been cited as leading to interviewer fatigue effects but not interviewee fatigue effects \parencite{paik_social_2013}.
      Indeed, my participants were happy to keep talking even during the longest interviews with the only exception being Alice Lemaire, and given that there was only one interviewer, fatigue would likely have been similar in each case.
      Instead, in the case of Rachel, the interview took place during a break in her work to which she had to return after about 35 minutes, short of the time when network questions would have been asked.
      In the case of Errol, he simply felt uncomfortable giving names despite explaining that he could give initials or just given names.

      Network data was therefore collected by the remaining \Sexpr{length(table(networks$Name))} participants, all while still conducting interviews in F\&C.
      Two name generator questions were posed to each participant as well as two name interpretor questions to elicit information about each alter who was named.
      The goal of the name generator questions is essentially to determine with whom participants interact, but there is more than one level of interaction possible.
      Two name generators were used as this has been found to be more effective, depending on the network measures in which one is interested, than relying on a lower-burden, single name generator \parencite{marin_simplifying_2007}.
      
      The first name generator question is the important matters question used for the GSS.
      This is not only has this generator been thoroughly investigated \parencite[\foreign{e.g.},][]{burt_whats_2012, ruan_content_1998}, but it is also one of the two questions used in the multiple generator approached that \citeauthor{marin_simplifying_2007}'s (\citeyear{marin_simplifying_2007}) examined.
      The question, along with the F\&C version used for this study, is reproduced here as sentence \ref{sent:name_generator_GSS}.
      While the translation was literally comprehensible for participants on the surface, it did sometimes need to be explained further so that participants could understand the sort of people I was asking them to name.
      The most common confusion was what was meant by ``important personal matters,'' as this was sometimes interpreted as being business matters or philosophical matters, leading to naming of people such as lawyers or those with whom they discuss topics such as politics.
      Another confusion, however, was whether the question was about discussing important matters specifically in F\&C rather than in any language, the latter being the intent.

      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item \label{sent:name_generator_GSS} From time to time, most people discuss important matters with other people. Looking back over the last six months -- that would be back to last August -- who are the people with whom you discussed an important personal matter? \parencite[p.~331]{burt_network_1984}
        \item[] \longtrans{Tous les temps en temps, le monde parle pour les affaires importantes avec d’autre monde. Si tu peux jongler pour les six derniers mois, qui sont les individus avec qui toi tu parles pour les affaires qui te sont importantes?}
      \end{enumerate}

      This name generator was originally found to yield of mean of 3.01 alters with a $SD$ of 1.77 \parencite[p.~125]{marsden_core_1987}, which is in line with those generated in the current study (mean $\approx$ \Sexpr{round(mean(table(networks[networks$`Alter Type` == "Core", "Name"])), 2)}, $SD \approx$ \Sexpr{round(sd(table(networks[networks$`Alter Type` == "Core", "Name"])), 2)}).
      These numbers for the important matters question may appear rather small, but this has been found to be one of the most robust questions for getting good results \parencite[p.~163]{marin_simplifying_2007}.
      Alters named in this way were coded as core alters.
      
      The second name generator question, sentence \ref{sent:name_generator_french}, was aimed at generating what were coded as non-core alters.
      The question focuses specifically on the use of F\&C to ensure that personal networks were not wholly made up of alters with whom participants only speak English as such networks would not provide any means of drawing connections between participants' subject pronoun usage in F\&C and their personal networks.
      Despite most participants referring to their language as \lexi{français} \gloss{French}, this question was at times extended to say \foreign{français ou créole} \gloss{French or Creole} for fear that participants might name only speakers of a single specific language variety otherwise.
      It was also often necessary to clarify that the question was asking them to name people with whom they spoke F\&C at all, not necessarily only F\&C, that come to mind, although the more frequent interlocutors were of greater interest than those with whom they interacted very little.
      This question resulted in a mean of \Sexpr{round(mean(table(networks[networks$`Alter Type` == "Non-Core", "Name"])), 2)} more named alters ($SD \approx$ \Sexpr{round(sd(table(networks[networks$`Alter Type` == "Non-Core", "Name"])), 2)}), bringing the total to a mean of \Sexpr{round(mean(table(networks$Name)), 2)} ($SD \approx$ \Sexpr{round(sd(table(networks$Name)), 2)}).
      These numbers themselves highlight that obtaining a fixed number of alters was not the goal.
      As has been noted, while doing so may help for comparability between networks, it can also lead to overlooking important ties or including unimportant ties \parencite[p.~345]{sharma_language_2020}.

      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item \label{sent:name_generator_french} Qui sont les personnes avec qui tu parles souvent français?
        \item[] \longtrans{Who are the people with whom you often speak French?}
      \end{enumerate}
        
      % Recall bias can be reduced by bringing certain contexts to the attention of the respondent (Marin 2004, as cited in Stark 2018:245)
      % Examples in sociolinguistics
        % Eckert (2000) simply asked participants who they were friends with at different points of interviews (80)
        % To collect alters, Sharma's (2017) participants were "asked to describe the main groups of people they interacted with on a regular basis, providing further details of each alter, including ethnicity, background, accent, frequency of interaction, domains of interaction, shared ties, and a relative closeness ranking" (400)
          % For analyses, Sharma (2017) excluded naming family members because they are not voluntarily chosen and yet would have made up a large proportion of their networks (400)
            % The motivation for emphasizing voluntary choices in her study isn't clear, but it would not be an issue here
            % L. Milroy (1980/1987) also discussed Hymes' (1974) idea of primary interaction, which is an interaction between two people which is strictly personal and wholly voluntary (84-85)

      With the list of alters generated, participants were asked two name interpretor questions immediately afterward.
      One of these questions, reproduced in sentence \ref{sent:interpret_ethnicity}, constituted a type of proxy report \parencite[p.~87]{cobb_answering_2018}.
      It has been suggested that these questions be asked during a follow-up meeting with participants as this lowers interviewee fatigue and increases accuracy \parencite[p.~245]{stark_collecting_2018}, but for the current study, the lack of any sign of fatigue from participants meant that the greater risk would have been attempting to set up follow-up meetings.
      Not only would participants perhaps lose their enthusiasm for partaking in the interim, but follow-ups would increase both the time needed to complete data collection and the cost of data collection, two factors for which resources were limited.

      It is reasonable to also doubt the accuracy of proxy reports in general.
      Previous work has found open-ended questions to yield the most highly accurate responses \parencite{cobb_proxy_2018}, which is in fact the sort of name interpretor question that sentence \ref{sent:interpret_ethnicity} represents.
      Additionally, as has previously been observed, even when accuracy in terms of agreement between the respondent and the person they are describing is low, what is often more important is the respondent's perception \parencite[p.~277]{cornwell_survey_2014}.
      While it would have been beneficial for the ethnicity question to know what the alters themselves would say, a participant perceiving alters as having one ethnicity or another makes up one half of common two part criteria for claiming an ethnicity, the first being that one sees oneself as a member of an ethnic group and the second being that others in the group accept the person as a member of the group.
      Essentially, if a Cajun describes an alter as Cajun, that alter most likely can pass as a Cajun, and indeed, as will be discussed in section \ref{sec:network_analyses}, agreement was high between participants when they were describing the ethnicities of shared alters.

      \begin{enumerate}[resume=sentences]
        \item Pour chaque personne sur cette liste, quoi c’est son éthnicité, c’est-à-dire son \foreign{ethnicity}? \label{sent:interpret_ethnicity}
        \item[] \longtrans{For each person on this list, what is their ethnicity, that is to say their ethnicity?}
        \item Pour chaque personne sur cette liste, combien souvent tu parles français avec? \label{sent:interpret_french}
        \item[] \longtrans{For each person on this list, how often do you speak French with them?}
      \end{enumerate}

      At times, participants needed some clarification as to what exactly they were being asked for the ethnicity question.
      This could take the form of misunderstanding whether they were being asked if they know what an alter would say rather than just what they themselves would say about the alter.
      The question was therefore often followed up with an explanation that their answer did not have to be exactly what their alter would say.
      Another form of clarification that was sometimes needed was what was meant by the term \lexi{ethnicity}.
      The word was repeated in English in the original question as \lexi{ethnicité} is not a widely used word in the community, but examples were also provided.
      Typically these examples included Cajun, Creole, American, Indian, and Latino, which was generally sufficient as an explanation.

      The second name interpretor question, reproduced in sentence \ref{sent:interpret_french}, aimed at obtaining the proportion of French used in discourse with each alter.
      This question was asked for each alter, non-core and core, as being named as a core alter (\foreign{i.e.}, as someone with whom a participant would discuss important matters) was not mutually exclusive with the possibility of speaking F\&C with that person, as well.
      There was generally no confusion related to this question.

    \subsection{Analyses}
      \label{sec:network_analyses}
      Generally, the analyses of participants' personal networks that were undertaken involved straightforward descriptive statistics.
      The major exception was the statistic used to quantify homophily, external-interal (EI) homophily \parencite{lizardo_social_2020}, given in Equation \ref{eq:ei_homophily}.
      EI homophily is calculated for each participant's personal social network.
      The external component is the count of all out-group alters, whereas the internal component is all in-group alters.
      In the present context, an in-group alter would be one who has the same ethnicity as ego (\foreign{i.e.}, the participant), and an out-group alter is any other alter.
      The statistic produces values from -1 to 1 where -1 represents perfect homophily and 1 the complete absence of homophily.

      \begin{enumerate}[label=\roman*., ref=\roman*, resume=equations]
        \item EI homophily $= \frac{\text{External} - \text{Internal}}{\text{External} + \text{Internal}}$ \label{eq:ei_homophily}
      \end{enumerate}

      The more important discussion in terms of analyses, however, is the way in which the ethnicities of alters were coded both from the perspective of personal networks and from the perspective of the whole network.
      When analyzing personal networks, it was necessary to decide how to code alters who were given multiple or compound ethnicities by participants.
      Multiple ethnicities refers to, for example, when an alter is described as both African-American and Creole.
      Compound ethnicities, on the other hand, included alters who were given labels that combined multiple categories into a single, more nuanced category such as Creole-African-American or Americanized Cajun.
      Maintaining these multiple and compound ethnicities as-is, while interesting to discuss and take account of qualitatively, also risks overlooking what are essentially homophilous relationships.
      When a Cajun participant describes an alter as an ``Americanized Cajun'', it is not likely that they see that alter as being completely ethnically distinct from themselves.
      The use of a qualifier does indeed suggest that the participant does not see this alter as being ethnically identical, but to deny the ethnic connection altogether would also be inaccurate.
      With that in mind, all multiple and compound ethnicities that included Creole were collapsed to simply Creole, and those that included Cajun were collapsed to simply Cajun.
      These changes are summarized in Table \ref{tab:collapsed_alter_ethnicities}, which also demonstrates that these cases made up a relatively small number of the total of \Sexpr{nrow(networks)} alters named.

      One special case remained which was an alter residing in Canada who was described Steven Marcel as Acadian.
      As was discussed in section \ref{sec:cajun_history}, Acadians are central to how Cajuns understand their own ethnic origin, so much so that some Louisianians will still use Acadian as a synonym for Cajun such as in the title of the annual Lafayette music festival: Festivals Acadiens et Créoles.
      There is therefore an argument for recoding this alter as Cajun, but this was not done because several other alters named by Steven were described as Cajun, suggesting that he made a distinction between these two labels.

